5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
In China their crescent shaped and filled with pork and cabbage

6
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.000
in Nepal they're called Momos and are fried with buffalo meat.

7
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.000
In Ireland they're soaked in Guinness gravy

8
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
and Italians filled them with spinach and call them Noki.

9
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
They can be steamed or fried and are found all over the world.

10
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
I'm talking of course about dumplings.

11
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Dumplings are a group of dishes where a filling is wrapped inside pieces of cooked dough.

12
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.000
They're basically dough envelopes with a filling inside.

13
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Filling can be anything from meat and fish to vegetables, tofu or cheese

14
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.000
and the dough is usually based on a starchy grain like wheat, rice, corn or potato.

15
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:05.000
In fact the English word dumpling comes from a 17th century adjective, dump, meaning dough like.

16
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
The really amazing thing about dumplings is that they're found all over the world.

17
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Over the centuries different countries and regions have experimented with flavours and fillings

18
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
to create something unique.

19
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Wherever in the world you are there's probably a special kind of dumpling for you.

20
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
In this programme we'll be sampling a dumpling from the West African country of Ghana.

21
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And as usual we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

22
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Great, but first I have a question for you, Beth.

23
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Probably the most famous British dumplings, Stuart dumplings, are cooked on top of a chicken or beef stew

24
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
that made from soot but what exactly is that?

25
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Is soot a wheat, b, potato or sea animal fat?

26
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
I think so it is made from animal fat.

27
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Okay Beth, we'll find out if that's the correct answer later in the programme.

28
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
The origins of dumplings are a mystery.

29
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Historians think the dish is very old but no one knows for sure when or where the first dumpling was cooked.

30
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
One theory puts the birthplace of the dumpling along the silk road,

31
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
linking China with central Asia and Turkey.

32
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
One way or another the dumpling journey through the Middle East and across Africa to Ghana,

33
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
where today it's a favourite way of adding carbohydrates to a dish, as well as soaking up sources and juices.

34
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:39.000
Kaffiri Agida is a businesswoman and fan of the Ghanaian dumpling called Kengki.

35
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Here she introduces Kengki to Ruth Alexander, presenter of the BBC World Service programme The Food Chain.

36
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
I love Kengki. If I don't have Kengki, this afternoon you've had some this afternoon.

37
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Yes, I love it. And it hits the spot.

38
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Absolutely. And it's a Gauwa, where the Gauwa is one of the tribes in Ghana and Kengki is the ass-table food.

39
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Even though it's eaten across the whole country.

40
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
How is it done eaten?

41
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Now we have to eat Kengki with what we call Chilisos.

42
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:21.000
But we also have the black sauce, which shrems fish and also of proteins in it.

43
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And then Yam Yam you go at it, you dig in.

44
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.000
So is this really satisfying comfort food?

45
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:36.000
It is very satisfying. In fact, Kengki is loved by most people who do manual works,

46
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
because it feels the tummy and it takes you almost a whole day before you, you feel hungry again.

47
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Kafiri says eating Kengki really hits the spot.

48
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.000
If something hits the spot, it's exactly what you wanted and totally satisfies you.

49
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Kengki dumplings are made from May's sour dough and eaten across Ghana.

50
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
For some tribes, Kengki is their staple food.

51
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:08.000
A basic and important type of food that is regularly eaten by a large portion of the population.

52
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
In Britain, for example, bread and eggs are staple foods.

53
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Kengki takes time to make. The May's needs to be soaked in water for a week.

54
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:25.000
But when they're ready and served with a hot chili sauce, Kafiri uses two phrases to show its time to eat.

55
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Yam Yam is used to say that food tastes or smells very good.

56
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
And again, is another exclamation, meaning don't wait.

57
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Start eating and eat as much as you like.

58
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:44.000
For Ghana, Kengki is comfort food, something which is enjoyable to eat and makes you feel happier.

59
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
And what's more, it fills your tummy or stomach.

60
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Whatever type you eat and wherever in the world you eat them, dumplings are a great way to spread a little love, including in Britain.

61
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Yes, it looks like we're back to my earlier question.

62
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
I asked you what the traditional British Suit dumpling is made from.

63
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Beth Gest, it was animal fat, which was the correct answer.

64
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Suit dumplings aren't the healthiest, but for some, they're certainly comfort food.

65
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Food that makes you feel happier because it tastes good or because it reminds you of home.

66
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Okay, let's recap the rest of the vocabulary we've learned in this program.

67
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Starting with the idiom hits the spot, meaning that something is satisfying and exactly what you wanted.

68
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:36.000
A staple food is a basic and important type of food that is regularly eaten by a large portion of the population.

69
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:42.000
The exclamation Yam Yam is used to say that food tastes or smells delicious.

70
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.000
If you say dig in, you're inviting someone to start eating as much as they want.

71
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And finally, tummy is an informal word for stomach.

